description: From Middle English profound, from Anglo-Norman profound, from Old French profont, from Latin profundus, from pro + fundus (“bottom; foundation”).

adjectives.description: profound (comparative more profound, superlative most profound)

entries.meaning: Descending far below the surface; opening or reaching to great depth; deep.
Intellectually deep; entering far into subjects; reaching to the bottom of a matter, or of a branch of learning; thorough
Characterized by intensity; deeply felt; pervading
examples: Of the profound corruption of this class there can be no doubt.

entries.meaning: Bending low, exhibiting or expressing deep humility; lowly; submissive
examples: What humble gestures! What profound reverence!

entries.meaning: (obsolete) The deep; the sea; the ocean.
examples: God, in the fathomlesse profound / Hath all his choice Commanders drown'd.

verbs.description: profound (third-person singular simple present profounds, present participle profounding, simple past and past participle profounded)

entries.meaning: (obsolete) To cause to sink deeply; to cause to dive or penetrate far down.
